rect HTTP requests to 127.0.0.1:32825. Focus on finding user management, authentication, and password-related endpoints.\n\n**RESULTS:**\n- **Main Platform:** IDOR Eats - Restaurant search platform with user accounts\n- **Authentication Endpoints:**\n  - `/login.php` - Login page (GET)\n  - `/register.php` - Registration page (GET)\n  - `/api/login.php` - Login API (POST)\n  - `/api/register.php` - Registration API (POST)\n  - `/logout.php` - Logout endpoint\n\n- **IDOR Vulnerable Endpoints:**\n  - `/api/get_favorite_restaurants.php?userId={X}` - **CONFIRMED IDOR** - No auth required\n  - `/api/change_password.php` - Password change endpoint (userId parameter in POST body)\n  - `/profile.php` - User profile page (hardcoded userId=15 in JS)\n\n- **Session Management:** PHPSESSID cookies, standard session handling\n- **Authentication Requirements:** Some endpoints require authentication, key IDOR endpoints do not\n- **User ID Pattern:** Numeric sequential IDs (1, 2, 3, etc.)\n- **Confirmed Users:** Users 1-11 exist; userId=7 has username "admin"; userId=1 has hint username "not_that_easy"\n\n**ASSESSMENT:** \nSufficient information gathered to proceed with IDOR exploitation. Key findings:\n1. `/api/change_password.php` accepts userId parameter - PRIMARY TARGET\n2. Authentication can be bypassed for data access but password changes may require valid session\n3. Admin user exists at userId=7 - high-value target\n4. Challenge hint suggests simple enumeration won\'t work - need to test parameter manipulation techniques\n\nReady to attempt exploitation of password change functionality through IDOR vulnerability.', 'proofs': '**Discovered Endpoints from HTML/JavaScript:**\n```\nGET /login.php - Login form with AJAX submission to /api/login.php\nGET /register.php - Registration form with AJAX to /api/register.php  \nGET /profile.php - Profile page with hardcoded userId=15 (accessible unauthenticated)\nPOST /api/login.php - Login API (parameters: username, password)\nPOST /ap